  28class Sequence(Generic[T], Iterable[T]):
  29    """
  30    Given an [iterator] function constructs a [Sequence] that returns values through the [Iterator]
  31    provided by that function.
  32    
  33    The values are evaluated lazily, and the sequence is potentially infinite.
  34    """
  35    _iter: SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], T]
  36
  37    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T]) -> None:
  38        super().__init__()
  39        if not isinstance(isinstance, SequenceTransform):
  40            iterable = SequenceTransform(iterable)
  41        self._iter = iterable
  42
  43    @overload
  44    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  45        ...
  46    @overload
  47    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  48        ...
  49    @overload
  50    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  51        ...
  52    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  53        """
  54        Returns a Sequence containing only elements matching the given [predicate].
  55
  56        Example 1:
  57        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
  58        >>> it(lst).filter(lambda x: x.startswith('a')).to_list()
  59        ['a1', 'a2']
  60
  61        Example 2:
  62        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
  63        >>> it(lst).filter(lambda x, i: x.startswith('a') or i % 2 == 0 ).to_list()
  64        ['a1', 'b2', 'a2']
  65        """
  66        return FilteringTransform(self, self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)).as_sequence()
  67
  68    @deprecated(reason="use `.filter(lambda x, idx: ... )` instead.")
  69    def filter_indexed(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  70        return self.filter(predicate)
  71
  72    def filter_is_instance(self, typ: Type[R]) -> Sequence[R]:
  73        """
  74        Returns a Sequence containing all elements that are instances of specified type parameter typ.
  75
  76        Example 1:
  77        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 1, 'b2', 3]
  78        >>> it(lst).filter_is_instance(int).to_list()
  79        [1, 3]
  80
  81        """
  82        return self.filter(lambda x: isinstance(x, typ)) # type: ignore

  84    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  85        ...
  86    @overload
  87    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  88        ...
  89    @overload
  90    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  91        ...
  92    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  93        """
  94        Returns a Sequence containing all elements not matching the given [predicate].
  95
  96        Example 1:
  97        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
  98        >>> it(lst).filter_not(lambda x: x.startswith('a')).to_list()
  99        ['b1', 'b2']
 100
 101        Example 2:
 102        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'a2', 'b1', 'b2']
 103        >>> it(lst).filter_not(lambda x, i: x.startswith('a') and i % 2 == 0 ).to_list()
 104        ['a2', 'b1', 'b2']
 105        """
 106        predicate = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
 107        return self.filter(lambda x: not predicate(x))
 108
 109    def filter_not_none(self) -> Sequence[T]:
 110        """
 111        Returns a Sequence containing all elements that are not `None`.
 112
 113        Example 1:
 114        >>> lst = [ 'a', None, 'b']
 115        >>> it(lst).filter_not_none().to_list()
 116        ['a', 'b']
 117        """
 118        return self.filter(lambda x: x is not None)

 121    def map(self, transform: Callable[[T], R]) -> Sequence[R]:

 126    @overload
 127    def map(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], R]) -> Sequence[R]:
 128        ...
 129    def map(self, transform: Callable[..., R]) -> Sequence[R]:
 130        """
 131        Returns a Sequence containing the results of applying the given [transform] function
 132        to each element in the original Sequence.
 133
 134        Example 1:
 135        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 136        >>> it(lst).map(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 137        [12, 13]
 138
 139        Example 2:
 140        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 141        >>> it(lst).map(lambda x, i: x['name'] + str(i)).to_list()
 142        ['A0', 'B1']
 143
 144        Example 3:
 145        >>> lst = ['hi', 'abc']
 146        >>> it(lst).map(len).to_list()
 147        [2, 3]
 148        """
 149        return MappingTransform(self, self._callback_overload_warpper(transform)).as_sequence()
 150    
 151    @deprecated(reason="use `.map(lambda x, idx: ... )` instead.")
 152    def map_indexed(self, transform: Callable[[T, int], R]) -> Sequence[R]:
 153        return self.map(transform)
 154    
 155    async def map_async(self, transform: Callable[..., Coroutine[Any, Any, R]]) -> Sequence[R]:
 156        """
 157        Similar to `.map()` but you can input a async transform then await it.
 158        """
 159        from asyncio import gather
 160        return it(await gather(*self.map(transform))) # type: ignore

 169    def map_not_none(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], Optional[R]]) -> Sequence[R]:

 171    def map_not_none(self, transform: Callable[..., Optional[R]]) -> Sequence[R]:
 172        """
 173        Returns a Sequence containing only the non-none results of applying the given [transform] function
 174        to each element in the original collection.
 175
 176        Example 1:
 177        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 178        >>> it(lst).map_not_none(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 179        [12]
 180        """
 181        return self.map(transform).filter_not_none() # type: ignore

 189    @overload
 190    def parallel_map(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], R], max_workers: Optional[int]=None, chunksize: int=1, executor: ParallelMappingTransform.Executor='Thread') -> Sequence[R]:
 191        ...
 192    def parallel_map(self, transform: Callable[..., R], max_workers: Optional[int]=None, chunksize: int=1, executor: ParallelMappingTransform.Executor='Thread') -> Sequence[R]:
 193        """
 194        Returns a Sequence containing the results of applying the given [transform] function
 195        to each element in the original Sequence.
 196
 197        Example 1:
 198        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 199        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 200        [12, 13]
 201
 202        Example 2:
 203        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 204        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x: x['age'], max_workers=2).to_list()
 205        [12, 13]
 206
 207        Example 3:
 208        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 209        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x, i: x['age'] + i, max_workers=2).to_list()
 210        [12, 14]
 211        """
 212        return ParallelMappingTransform(self, self._callback_overload_warpper(transform), max_workers, chunksize, executor).as_sequence()

 223    def find(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 224        """
 225        Returns the first element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if no such element was found.
 226        
 227        Example 1:
 228        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 229        >>> it(lst).find(lambda x: x == 'b')
 230        'b'
 231        """
 232        return self.first_or_none(predicate)
 233    
 234    def find_last(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 235        """
 236        Returns the last element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if no such element was found.
 237        
 238        Example 1:
 239        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 240        >>> it(lst).find_last(lambda x: x == 'b')
 241        'b'
 242        """
 243        return self.last_or_none(predicate)

 254    @overload
 255    def first(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T:
 256        ...
 257    def first(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 258        """
 259        Returns first element.
 260
 261        Example 1:
 262        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 263        >>> it(lst).first()
 264        'a'
 265
 266        Example 2:
 267        >>> lst = []
 268        >>> it(lst).first()
 269        Traceback (most recent call last):
 270        ...
 271        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 272
 273        Example 3:
 274        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 275        >>> it(lst).first(lambda x: x == 'b')
 276        'b'
 277
 278        Example 4:
 279        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 280        >>> it(lst).first(lambda x: x == 'd')
 281        Traceback (most recent call last):
 282        ...
 283        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 284
 285        Example 5:
 286        >>> lst = [None]
 287        >>> it(lst).first() is None
 288        True
 289        """
 290        for e in self:
 291            if predicate is None or predicate(e):
 292                return e
 293        raise ValueError("Sequence is empty.")

 306    def first_not_none_of(self: Sequence[Optional[R]], transform: Callable[[Optional[R], int, Sequence[Optional[R]]], Optional[R]]) -> R:
 307        ...
 308    def first_not_none_of(self: Sequence[Optional[R]], transform: Optional[Callable[..., Optional[R]]] = None) -> R:
 309        """
 310        Returns the first non-`None` result of applying the given [transform] function to each element in the original collection.
 311
 312        Example 1:
 313        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 12}]
 314        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of(lambda x: x['age'])
 315        12
 316
 317        Example 2:
 318        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 319        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of(lambda x: x['age'])
 320        Traceback (most recent call last):
 321        ...
 322        ValueError: No element of the Sequence was transformed to a non-none value.
 323        """
 324
 325        v = self.first_not_none_of_or_none() if transform is None else self.first_not_none_of_or_none(transform)
 326        if v is None:
 327            raise ValueError('No element of the Sequence was transformed to a non-none value.')
 328        return v

 341        ...
 342    def first_not_none_of_or_none(self, transform: Optional[Callable[..., T]] = None) -> T:
 343        """
 344        Returns the first non-`None` result of applying the given [transform] function to each element in the original collection.
 345
 346        Example 1:
 347        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 12}]
 348        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of_or_none(lambda x: x['age'])
 349        12
 350
 351        Example 2:
 352        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 353        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of_or_none(lambda x: x['age']) is None
 354        True
 355        """
 356        if transform is None:
 357            return self.first_or_none()
 358        return self.map_not_none(transform).first_or_none()

 372    def first_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 373        """
 374        Returns the first element, or `None` if the Sequence is empty.
 375
 376        Example 1:
 377        >>> lst = []
 378        >>> it(lst).first_or_none() is None
 379        True
 380
 381        Example 2:
 382        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 383        >>> it(lst).first_or_none()
 384        'a'
 385
 386        Example 2:
 387        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 388        >>> it(lst).first_or_none(lambda x: x == 'b')
 389        'b'
 390        """
 391        return next(iter(self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate)), None)

 405        ...
 406    def first_or_default(self, predicate: Union[Callable[..., bool], T], default: Optional[T] = None) -> T: # type: ignore
 407        """
 408        Returns the first element, or the given [default] if the Sequence is empty.
 409
 410        Example 1:
 411        >>> lst = []
 412        >>> it(lst).first_or_default('a')
 413        'a'
 414
 415        Example 2:
 416        >>> lst = ['b']
 417        >>> it(lst).first_or_default('a')
 418        'b'
 419        
 420        Example 3:
 421        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 422        >>> it(lst).first_or_default(lambda x: x == 'b', 'd')
 423        'b'
 424
 425        Example 4:
 426        >>> lst = []
 427        >>> it(lst).first_or_default(lambda x: x == 'b', 'd')
 428        'd'
 429        """
 430        if isinstance(predicate, Callable):
 431            return self.first_or_none(predicate) or default # type: ignore
 432        else:
 433            default = predicate
 434        return self.first_or_none() or default

 438        ...

 446    def last(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T:
 447        ...
 448    def last(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 449        """
 450        Returns last element.
 451
 452        Example 1:
 453        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 454        >>> it(lst).last()
 455        'c'
 456
 457        Example 2:
 458        >>> lst = []
 459        >>> it(lst).last()
 460        Traceback (most recent call last):
 461        ...
 462        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 463        """
 464        v = self.last_or_none(predicate) if predicate is not None else self.last_or_none()
 465        if v is None:
 466            raise ValueError('Sequence is empty.')
 467        return v
 468
 469    @overload
 470    def last_or_none(self) -> Optional[T]:
 471        ...
 472    @overload
 473    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 474        ...
 475    @overload
 476    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 477        ...
 478    @overload
 479    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 480        ...
 481    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 482        """
 483        Returns the last element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if no such element was found.
 484
 485        Exmaple 1:
 486        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 487        >>> it(lst).last_or_none()
 488        'c'
 489
 490        Exmaple 2:
 491        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 492        >>> it(lst).last_or_none(lambda x: x != 'c')
 493        'b'
 494
 495        Exmaple 3:
 496        >>> lst = []
 497        >>> it(lst).last_or_none(lambda x: x != 'c') is None
 498        True
 499        """
 500        last: Optional[T] = None
 501        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
 502            last = i
 503        return last
 504    
 505    def index_of(self, element: T) -> int:
 506        """
 507        Returns first index of [element], or -1 if the collection does not contain element.
 508         
 509        Example 1:
 510        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 511        >>> it(lst).index_of('b')
 512        1
 513
 514        Example 2:
 515        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 516        >>> it(lst).index_of('d')
 517        -1
 518        """
 519        for i, x in enumerate(self._iter):
 520            if x == element:
 521                return i
 522        return -1
 523    
 524    def last_index_of(self, element: T) -> int:
 525        """
 526         Returns last index of [element], or -1 if the collection does not contain element.
 527         
 528        Example 1:
 529        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'b']
 530        >>> it(lst).last_index_of('b')
 531        3
 532
 533        Example 2:
 534        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 535        >>> it(lst).last_index_of('d')
 536        -1
 537        """
 538        seq = self.reversed()
 539        last_idx = len(seq) - 1;
 540        for i, x in enumerate(seq):
 541            if x == element:
 542                return last_idx - i
 543        return -1
 544

 553        ...
 554    def index_of_first(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> int:
 555        """
 556        Returns first index of element matching the given [predicate], or -1 if no such element was found.
 557         
 558        Example 1:
 559        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 560        >>> it(lst).index_of_first(lambda x: x == 'b')
 561        1
 562
 563        Example 2:
 564        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 565        >>> it(lst).index_of_first(lambda x: x == 'd')
 566        -1
 567        """
 568        predicate = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
 569        for i, x in enumerate(self._iter):
 570            if predicate(x):
 571                return i
 572        return -1
 573    
 574    @overload
 575    def index_of_last(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> int:
 576        ...
 577    @overload
 578    def index_of_last(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> int:
 579        ...
 580    @overload
 581    def index_of_last(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> int:
 582        ...
 583    def index_of_last(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> int:
 584        """
 585        Returns last index of element matching the given [predicate], or -1 if no such element was found.
 586         
 587        Example 1:
 588        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'b']
 589        >>> it(lst).index_of_last(lambda x: x == 'b')
 590        3
 591
 592        Example 2:
 593        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 594        >>> it(lst).index_of_last(lambda x: x == 'd')
 595        -1
 596        """
 597        seq = self.reversed()
 598        last_idx = len(seq) - 1;
 599        predicate = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
 600        for i, x in enumerate(seq):
 601            if predicate(x):
 602                return last_idx - i
 603        return -1
 604
 605    @overload
 606    def single(self) -> T:
 607        ...
 608    @overload

 610        ...
 611    @overload
 612    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> T:
 613        ...
 614    @overload
 615    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T:
 616        ...
 617    def single(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 618        """
 619        Returns the single element matching the given [predicate], or throws exception if there is no
 620        or more than one matching element.
 621
 622        Exmaple 1:
 623        >>> lst = ['a']
 624        >>> it(lst).single()
 625        'a'
 626
 627        Exmaple 2:
 628        >>> lst = []
 629        >>> it(lst).single() is None
 630        Traceback (most recent call last):
 631        ...
 632        ValueError: Sequence contains no element matching the predicate.
 633
 634        Exmaple 2:
 635        >>> lst = ['a', 'b']
 636        >>> it(lst).single() is None
 637        Traceback (most recent call last):
 638        ...
 639        ValueError: Sequence contains more than one matching element.
 640        """
 641        single: Optional[T] = None
 642        found = False
 643        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
 644            if found:
 645                raise ValueError('Sequence contains more than one matching element.')
 646            single = i
 647            found = True
 648        if single is None:
 649            raise ValueError('Sequence contains no element matching the predicate.')
 650        return single
 651
 652    @overload
 653    def single_or_none(self) -> Optional[T]:
 654        ...
 655    @overload
 656    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 657        ...
 658    @overload
 659    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 660        ...
 661    @overload
 662    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 663        ...
 664    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 665        """
 666        Returns the single element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if element was not found
 667        or more than one element was found.
 668
 669        Exmaple 1:
 670        >>> lst = ['a']
 671        >>> it(lst).single_or_none()
 672        'a'
 673
 674        Exmaple 2:
 675        >>> lst = []
 676        >>> it(lst).single_or_none() is None
 677        True
 678
 679        Exmaple 2:
 680        >>> lst = ['a', 'b']
 681        >>> it(lst).single_or_none() is None
 682        True
 683        """
 684        single: Optional[T] = None
 685        found = False
 686        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
 687            if found:
 688                return None
 689            single = i
 690            found = True
 691        if not found:
 692            return None
 693        return single

 695    # noinspection PyShadowingNames
 696    def drop(self, n: int) -> Sequence[T]:
 697        """
 698        Returns a Sequence containing all elements except first [n] elements.
 699
 700        Example 1:
 701        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 702        >>> it(lst).drop(0).to_list()
 703        ['a', 'b', 'c']
 704
 705        Example 2:
 706        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 707        >>> it(lst).drop(1).to_list()
 708        ['b', 'c']
 709
 710        Example 2:
 711        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 712        >>> it(lst).drop(4).to_list()
 713        []
 714        """
 715        if n < 0:
 716            raise ValueError(f'Requested element count {n} is less than zero.')
 717        if n == 0:
 718            return self
 719
 720        return DropTransform(self, n).as_sequence()

 785    def take(self, n: int) -> Sequence[T]:
 786        """
 787        Returns an Sequence containing first [n] elements.
 788
 789        Example 1:
 790        >>> a = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 791        >>> it(a).take(0).to_list()
 792        []
 793
 794        Example 2:
 795        >>> a = ['a', 'b', 'c']

 799        if n < 0:
 800            raise ValueError(f'Requested element count {n} is less than zero.')

 802            return Sequence([])
 803        return TakeTransform(self, n).as_sequence()

 826    def take_last(self, n: int) -> Sequence[T]:
 827        """
 828        Returns an Sequence containing last [n] elements.
 829
 830        Example 1:
 831        >>> a = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 832        >>> it(a).take_last(0).to_list()
 833        []
 834
 835        Example 2:
 836        >>> a = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 837        >>> it(a).take_last(2).to_list()
 838        ['b', 'c']
 839        """
 840        if n < 0:
 841            raise ValueError(f'Requested element count {n} is less than zero.')
 842        if n == 0:
 843            return Sequence([])
 844
 845        return self.drop(len(self) - n)

 847    # noinspection PyShadowingNames
 848    def sorted(self) -> Sequence[T]:
 849        """
 850        Returns an Sequence that yields elements of this Sequence sorted according to their natural sort order.
 851
 852        Example 1:
 853        >>> lst = ['b', 'a', 'e', 'c']
 854        >>> it(lst).sorted().to_list()
 855        ['a', 'b', 'c', 'e']
 856
 857         Example 2:
 858        >>> lst = [2, 1, 4, 3]
 859        >>> it(lst).sorted().to_list()
 860        [1, 2, 3, 4]
 861        """
 862        lst = list(self)
 863        lst.sort() # type: ignore
 864        return it(lst)

 875        ...
 876    def sorted_by(self, key_selector: Callable[..., SupportsRichComparisonT]) -> Sequence[T]:
 877        """
 878        Returns a sequence that yields elements of this sequence sorted according to natural sort
 879        order of the value returned by specified [key_selector] function.
 880
 881        Example 1:
 882        >>> lst = [ {'name': 'A', 'age': 12 }, {'name': 'C', 'age': 10 }, {'name': 'B', 'age': 11 } ]
 883        >>> it(lst).sorted_by(lambda x: x['name']).to_list()
 884        [{'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, {'name': 'B', 'age': 11}, {'name': 'C', 'age': 10}]
 885        >>> it(lst).sorted_by(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 886        [{'name': 'C', 'age': 10}, {'name': 'B', 'age': 11}, {'name': 'A', 'age': 12}]
 887        """
 888        lst = list(self)
 889        lst.sort(key=self._callback_overload_warpper(key_selector))
 890        return it(lst)

 892    def sorted_descending(self) -> Sequence[T]:
 893        """
 894        Returns a Sequence of all elements sorted descending according to their natural sort order.
 895
 896        Example 1:
 897        >>> lst = ['b', 'c', 'a']
 898        >>> it(lst).sorted_descending().to_list()
 899        ['c', 'b', 'a']

 901        return self.sorted().reversed()

 927    def sorted_with(self, comparator: Callable[[T, T], int]) -> Sequence[T]:
 928        """
 929        Returns a sequence that yields elements of this sequence sorted according to the specified [comparator].
 930
 931        Example 1:
 932        >>> lst = ['aa', 'bbb', 'c']
 933        >>> it(lst).sorted_with(lambda a, b: len(a)-len(b)).to_list()

 949        ...
 950    def associate(self, transform: Callable[..., Tuple[K, V]]) -> Dict[K, V]:
 951        """
 952        Returns a [Dict] containing key-value Tuple provided by [transform] function
 953        applied to elements of the given Sequence.
 954
 955        Example 1:
 956        >>> lst = ['1', '2', '3']
 957        >>> it(lst).associate(lambda x: (int(x), x))
 958        {1: '1', 2: '2', 3: '3'}
 959        """
 960        transform = self._callback_overload_warpper(transform)
 961        dic: Dict[K, V] = dict()
 962        for i in self:
 963            k, v = transform(i)
 964            dic[k] = v
 965        return dic

 979    def associate_by(self, key_selector: Callable[..., K],
 980                     value_transform: Optional[Callable[[T], V]] = None) -> Union[Dict[K, T], Dict[K, V]]:
 981        """
 982        Returns a [Dict] containing key-value Tuple provided by [transform] function
 983        applied to elements of the given Sequence.
 984

 986        >>> lst = ['1', '2', '3']

 992        >>> it(lst).associate_by(lambda x: int(x), lambda x: x+x)
 993        {1: '11', 2: '22', 3: '33'}
 994
 995        """
 996        key_selector = self._callback_overload_warpper(key_selector)
 997
 998        dic: Dict[K, Any] = dict()
 999        for i in self:
1000            k = key_selector(i)
1001            dic[k] = i if value_transform is None else value_transform(i)
1002        return dic

1044

1047        >>> it(lst).all(lambda x: x > 0)
1048        True
1049        >>> it(lst).all(lambda x: x > 1)
1050        False
1051        """
1052        predicate = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
1053        for i in self:
1054            if not predicate(i):
1055                return False
1056        return True

1095        ...
1096    def count(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> int:
1097        """
1098        Returns the number of elements in the Sequence that satisfy the specified [predicate] function.
1099
1100        Example 1:
1101        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1102        >>> it(lst).count()
1103        3
1104        >>> it(lst).count(lambda x: x > 0)
1105        3
1106        >>> it(lst).count(lambda x: x > 2)
1107        1
1108        """
1109        if predicate is None:
1110            return len(self)
1111        predicate = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
1112        return sum(1 for i in self if predicate(i))

1128    def element_at(self, index: int) -> T:
1129        """
1130        Returns the element at the specified [index] in the Sequence.
1131
1132        Example 1:
1133        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]

1141        ...

1143        """
1144        return self.element_at_or_else(index, lambda index: throw(IndexError(f'Index {index} out of range')))

1166    def element_at_or_else(self, index: int, default: Union[Callable[[int], T], T, None]) -> Union[Optional[T], T]:
1167        """
1168        Returns the element at the specified [index] in the Sequence or the [default] value if the index is out of bounds.
1169
1170        Example 1:

1172        >>> it(lst).element_at_or_else(1, lambda x: 'default')
1173        2
1174        >>> it(lst).element_at_or_else(4, lambda x: 'default')
1175        'default'
1176
1177        """
1178        if (index < 0):
1179            return default(index) if callable(default) else default
1180        
1181        for i, e in enumerate(self):
1182            if i == index:
1183                return e
1184        return default(index) if callable(default) else default
1185    
1186
1187    def element_at_or_default(self, index: int, default: T) -> T:
1188        """
1189        Returns the element at the specified [index] in the Sequence or the [default] value if the index is out of bounds.
1190
1191        Example 1:
1192        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1193        >>> it(lst).element_at_or_default(1, 'default')
1194        2
1195        >>> it(lst).element_at_or_default(4, 'default')
1196        'default'
1197
1198        """
1199        return self.element_at_or_else(index, default)
1200

1202    def element_at_or_none(self, index: int) -> Optional[T]:
1203        """
1204        Returns the element at the specified [index] in the Sequence or None if the index is out of bounds.
1205
1206        Example 1:
1207        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1208        >>> it(lst).element_at_or_none(1)
1209        2
1210        >>> it(lst).element_at_or_none(4) is None
1211        True
1212        """
1213        return self.element_at_or_else(index, None)

1215    def distinct(self) -> Sequence[T]:
1216        """
1217        Returns a new Sequence containing the distinct elements of the given Sequence.
1218
1219        Example 1:
1220        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3, 1, 2, 3]
1221        >>> it(lst).distinct().to_list()
1222        [1, 2, 3]
1223
1224        Example 2:
1225        >>> lst = [(1, 'A'), (1, 'A'), (1, 'A'), (2, 'A'), (3, 'C'), (3, 'D')]
1226        >>> it(lst).distinct().sorted().to_list()
1227        [(1, 'A'), (2, 'A'), (3, 'C'), (3, 'D')]
1228
1229        """
1230        return DistinctTransform(self).as_sequence()

1252    @overload
1253    def reduce(self, accumulator: Callable[[T, T], T]) -> T:
1254        ...
1255    @overload
1256    def reduce(self, accumulator: Callable[[R, T], R], initial: R) -> R:
1257        ...
1258    def reduce(self, accumulator: Callable[..., R], initial: Optional[R] = None) -> Optional[R]:
1259        """
1260        Returns the result of applying the specified [accumulator] function to the given Sequence's elements.
1261
1262        Example 1:
1263        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1264        >>> it(lst).reduce(lambda x, y: x+y)
1265        6
1266        """
1267        result: Optional[R] = initial
1268        for i, e in enumerate(self):
1269            if i == 0 and initial is None:
1270                result = e # type: ignore
1271                continue
1272            
1273            result = accumulator(result, e)
1274        return result
1275    
1276    def fold(self, initial: R, accumulator: Callable[[R, T], R]) -> R:
1277        """
1278        Returns the result of applying the specified [accumulator] function to the given Sequence's elements.
1279
1280        Example 1:
1281        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1282        >>> it(lst).fold(0, lambda x, y: x+y)
1283        6
1284        """
1285        return self.reduce(accumulator, initial)

1323        ...

1326        ...
1327    def max_by_or_none(self, selector: Callable[[T], Union[float, int]]) -> Optional[T]:
1328        """
1329        Returns the first element yielding the largest value of the given function
1330        or `none` if there are no elements.
1331
1332        Example 1:
1333        >>> lst = [ { "name": "A", "num": 100 }, { "name": "B", "num": 200 }]
1334        >>> it(lst).max_by_or_none(lambda x: x["num"])
1335        {'name': 'B', 'num': 200}
1336
1337        Example 2:
1338        >>> lst = []
1339        >>> it(lst).max_by_or_none(lambda x: x["num"])
1340        """
1341
1342        max_item = None
1343        max_val = None
1344
1345        for item in self:
1346            val = selector(item)
1347            if max_val is None or val > max_val:
1348                max_item = item
1349                max_val = val
1350        
1351        return max_item

1362        Returns the first element yielding the largest value of the given function.

1371        >>> it(lst).max_by(lambda x: x["num"])

1373        ...
1374        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
1375        """
1376        max_item = self.max_by_or_none(selector)
1377        if max_item is None:
1378            raise ValueError("Sequence is empty.")

1585    def flat_map(self, transform: Callable[..., Iterable[R]]) -> Sequence[R]:
1586        """
1587        Returns a single list of all elements yielded from results of [transform]
1588        function being invoked on each element of original collection.
1589
1590        Example 1:
1591        >>> lst = [['a', 'b'], ['c'], ['d', 'e']]
1592        >>> it(lst).flat_map(lambda x: x).to_list()

1594        """
1595        return self.map(transform).flatten()

1617    def group_by(self, key_selector: Callable[..., K]) -> Sequence[Grouping[K, T]]:
1618        """
1619        Returns a dictionary with keys being the result of [key_selector] function being invoked on each element of original collection
1620        and values being the corresponding elements of original collection.
1621
1622        Example 1:

1629    @overload

1637        ...
1638    def group_by_to(self, destination: Dict[K, List[T]], key_selector: Callable[..., K]) -> Dict[K, List[T]]:
1639        """
1640        Returns a dictionary with keys being the result of [key_selector] function being invoked on each element of original collection
1641        and values being the corresponding elements of original collection.
1642
1643        Example 1:
1644        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
1645        >>> it(lst).group_by_to({}, lambda x: x%2)
1646        {1: [1, 3, 5], 0: [2, 4]}
1647        """
1648        key_selector = self._callback_overload_warpper(key_selector)
1649        for e in self:
1650            k = key_selector(e)
1651            if k not in destination:
1652                destination[k] = []
1653            destination[k].append(e)
1654        return destination

1728        """
1729        Invokes [action] function on each element of the given Sequence.
1730
1731        Example 1:
1732        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1733        >>> it(lst).on_each(lambda x: print(x)) and None
1734        a
1735        b
1736        c
1737
1738        Example 2:
1739        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1740        >>> it(lst).on_each(lambda x, i: print(x, i)) and None
1741        a 0
1742        b 1
1743        c 2
1744        """
1745        action = self._callback_overload_warpper(action)
1746        for i in self:
1747            action(i)
1748        return self

1794        """
1795        Returns a new Sequence of tuples, where each tuple contains two elements.
1796        
1797        Example 1:
1798        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1799        >>> lst2 = [1, 2, 3]
1800        >>> it(lst1).zip(lst2).to_list()
1801        [('a', 1), ('b', 2), ('c', 3)]
1802
1803        Example 2:
1804        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1805        >>> lst2 = [1, 2, 3]
1806        >>> it(lst1).zip(lst2, lambda x, y: x + '__' +str( y)).to_list()
1807        ['a__1', 'b__2', 'c__3']
1808        """
1809        if transform is None:
1810            transform = lambda *x:(*x,)
1811        return MergingTransform(self, other, transform).as_sequence()
1812

1819    def zip_with_next(self, transform: Optional[Callable[[T, T], Any]]=None) -> Sequence[Any]:
1820        """
1821        Returns a sequence containing the results of applying the given [transform] function
1822        to an each pair of two adjacent elements in this sequence.
1823        
1824        Example 1:
1825        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1826        >>> it(lst).zip_with_next(lambda x, y: x + '__' + y).to_list()
1827        ['a__b', 'b__c']
1828
1829        Example 2:
1830        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1831        >>> it(lst).zip_with_next().to_list()
1832        [('a', 'b'), ('b', 'c')]
1833        """
1834        return MergingWithNextTransform(self, transform or (lambda a, b: (a, b))).as_sequence()

1860        ...
1861    def unzip(self, transform: Union[Optional[Callable[..., Tuple[Any, Any]]], bool]=None, as_sequence: bool=False) -> Any: # type: ignore
1862        """
1863        Returns a pair of lists, where first list is built from the first values of each pair from this array, second list is built from the second values of each pair from this array.
1864
1865        Example 1:
1866        >>> lst = [{'name': 'a', 'age': 11}, {'name': 'b', 'age': 12}, {'name': 'c', 'age': 13}]
1867        >>> a, b = it(lst).unzip(lambda x: (x['name'], x['age']))
1868        >>> a
1869        ['a', 'b', 'c']
1870        >>> b
1871        [11, 12, 13]
1872        
1873        Example 1:
1874        >>> lst = [('a', 11), ('b', 12), ('c', 13)]
1875        >>> a, b = it(lst).unzip()
1876        >>> a
1877        ['a', 'b', 'c']
1878        >>> b
1879        [11, 12, 13]
1880        """
1881        it = self
1882        if isinstance(transform, bool):
1883            as_sequence = transform
1884            transform = None
1885
1886        if transform is not None:
1887            transform = self._callback_overload_warpper(transform)
1888            it = it.map(transform)
1889        
1890        a = it.map(lambda x: x[0]) # type: ignore
1891        b = it.map(lambda x: x[1]) # type: ignore
1892
1893        if not as_sequence:
1894            return a.to_list(), b.to_list()
1895        return a, b

1904        >>> it(lst).with_index().to_list()
1905        [IndexedValue(0, a), IndexedValue(1, b), IndexedValue(2, c)]
1906        """
1907        return self.indexed()

1965        ...
1966    def partition(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool], as_sequence: bool=False):
1967        """
1968        Partitions the elements of the given Sequence into two groups,
1969        the first group containing the elements for which the predicate returns true,
1970        and the second containing the rest.
1971
1972        Example 1:
1973        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', '2']
1974        >>> it(lst).partition(lambda x: x.isalpha())
1975        (['a', 'b', 'c'], ['2'])
1976
1977        Example 2:
1978        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', '2']
1979        >>> it(lst).partition(lambda _, i: i % 2 == 0)
1980        (['a', 'c'], ['b', '2'])
1981        """
1982        predicate_a = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
1983        predicate_b = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
1984        part_a = self.filter(predicate_a)
1985        part_b = self.filter(lambda x: not predicate_b(x))
1986        if not as_sequence:
1987            return part_a.to_list(), part_b.to_list()
1988        return part_a, part_b 
1989

1999        return self.partition(predicate, as_sequence) # type: ignore

2041        """

2057        [['a', 'b', 'c'], ['c', 'd', 'e'], ['e', 'f']]

2091    def concat(self, *other: Sequence[T]) -> Sequence[T]:
2092        """
2093        Returns a Sequence of all elements of the given Sequence, followed by all elements of the given Sequence.
2094

2096        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']

2105        >>> it(lst1).concat(lst2, lst3).to_list()
2106        ['a', 'b', 'c', 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
2107        """
2108        return ConcatTransform([self, *other]).as_sequence()

2110    def intersect(self, *other: Sequence[T]) -> Sequence[T]:
2111        """
2112        Returns a set containing all elements that are contained by both this collection and the specified collection.
2113
2114        The returned set preserves the element iteration order of the original collection.
2115
2116        To get a set containing all elements that are contained at least in one of these collections use union.
2117
2118        Example 1:
2119        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2120        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b2', 'c']
2121        >>> it(lst1).intersect(lst2).to_list()
2122        ['c']
2123
2124        Example 2:
2125        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2126        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b', 'c']
2127        >>> lst3 = ['a3', 'b', 'c3']
2128        >>> it(lst1).intersect(lst2, lst3).to_list()
2129        ['b']
2130
2131
2132        Example 1:
2133        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'a', 'c']
2134        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b2', 'a']
2135        >>> it(lst1).intersect(lst2).to_list()
2136        ['a']
2137        """
2138        return IntersectionTransform([self, *other]).as_sequence()
2139    
2140    def union(self, *other: Sequence[T]) -> Sequence[T]:
2141        """
2142        Returns a set containing all distinct elements from both collections.
2143
2144        The returned set preserves the element iteration order of the original collection. Those elements of the other collection that are unique are iterated in the end in the order of the other collection.
2145
2146        To get a set containing all elements that are contained in both collections use intersect.
2147
2148        Example 1:
2149        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2150        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b2', 'c']
2151        >>> it(lst1).union(lst2).to_list()
2152        ['a', 'b', 'c', 'a2', 'b2']
2153
2154        Example 2:
2155        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2156        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b', 'c']
2157        >>> lst3 = ['a3', 'b', 'c3']
2158        >>> it(lst1).union(lst2, lst3).to_list()
2159        ['a', 'b', 'c', 'a2', 'a3', 'c3']
2160
2161
2162        Example 1:
2163        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'a', 'c']
2164        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b2', 'a']
2165        >>> it(lst1).union(lst2).to_list()
2166        ['a', 'c', 'a2', 'b2']
2167        """
2168        return self.concat(*other).distinct()

2189    def progress(self, progress_func: Callable[[Iterable[T]], Iterable[T]]) -> Sequence[T]:
2190        ...
2191    def progress(self, progress_func: Union[Callable[[Iterable[T]], Iterable[T]], Literal['tqdm'], Literal['tqdm_rich'], None ] = None) -> Sequence[T]:
2192        """
2193        Returns a Sequence that enable a progress bar for the given Sequence.
2194        
2195        Example 1:
2196        >>> from tqdm import tqdm
2197        >>> from time import sleep
2198        >>> it(range(10)).progress(lambda x: tqdm(x, total=len(x))).parallel_map(lambda x: sleep(0.), max_workers=5).to_list() and None
2199        >>> for _ in it(list(range(10))).progress(lambda x: tqdm(x, total=len(x))).to_list(): pass
2200        """
2201        if progress_func is not None and callable(progress_func):
2202            return ProgressTransform(self, progress_func).as_sequence()
2203        
2204        def import_tqdm():
2205            if progress_func == 'tqdm_rich':
2206                from tqdm.rich import tqdm
2207            else:
2208                from tqdm import tqdm
2209            return tqdm
2210
2211        try:
2212            tqdm = import_tqdm()
2213        except ImportError:
2214            from pip import main as pip
2215            pip(['install', 'tqdm'])
2216            tqdm = import_tqdm()
2217        
2218        return it(tqdm(self, total=len(self)))

2221    def typing_as(self, typ: Type[R]) -> Sequence[R]:
2222        """
2223        Cast the element as specific Type to gain code completion base on type annotations.
2224        """
2225        el = self.first_not_none_of_or_none()
2226        if el is None or isinstance(el, typ) or not isinstance(el, dict):
2227            return self # type: ignore
2228
2229        class AttrDict(Dict[str, Any]):
2230            def __init__(self, value: Dict[str, Any]) -> None:
2231                super().__init__(**value)
2232                setattr(self, '__dict__', value)
2233                self.__getattr__  = value.__getitem__
2234                self.__setattr__ = value.__setattr__ # type: ignore
2235        return self.map(AttrDict) # type: ignore  # use https://github.com/cdgriffith/Box ?

2260    def to_dict(self, transform: Optional[Callable[..., Tuple[K, V]]]=None) -> Dict[K, V]:
2261        """
2262        Returns a [Dict] containing key-value Tuple provided by [transform] function
2263        applied to elements of the given Sequence.
2264
2265        Example 1:
2266        >>> lst = ['1', '2', '3']
2267        >>> it(lst).to_dict(lambda x: (int(x), x))
2268        {1: '1', 2: '2', 3: '3'}
2269
2270        Example 2:
2271        >>> lst = [(1, '1'), (2, '2'), (3, '3')]
2272        >>> it(lst).to_dict()
2273        {1: '1', 2: '2', 3: '3'}
2274        """
2275        return self.associate(transform or (lambda x: x))

2298    def let(self, block: Callable[[Sequence[T]], R]) -> R:
2299        """
2300        Calls the specified function [block] with `self` value as its argument and returns its result.
2301            
2302        Example 1:
2303        >>> it(['a', 'b', 'c']).let(lambda x: x.map(lambda y: y + '!')).to_list()
2304        ['a!', 'b!', 'c!']
2305        """
2306        return block(self)

2308    def also(self, block: Callable[[Sequence[T]], Any]) -> Sequence[T]:
2309        """
2310        Calls the specified function [block] with `self` value as its argument and returns `self` value.
2311            
2312        Example 1:
2313        >>> it(['a', 'b', 'c']).also(lambda x: x.map(lambda y: y + '!')).to_list()
2314        ['a', 'b', 'c']
2315        """
2316        block(self)

2341    def __iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
2342        return self.__do_iter()
2343    
2344    def __do_iter(self) -> Iterator[T]:
2345        yield from self._iter

2348        return len(self._iter)

2350    @overload
2351    def _callback_overload_warpper(self, callback: Callable[[T], R]) -> Callable[[T], R]:
2352        ...
2353    @overload
2354    def _callback_overload_warpper(self, callback: Callable[[T, int], R]) -> Callable[[T], R]:
2355        ...
2356    @overload
2357    def _callback_overload_warpper(self, callback: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], R]) -> Callable[[T], R]:
2358        ...
2359    def _callback_overload_warpper(self, callback: Callable[..., R]) -> Callable[[T], R]:
2360        if hasattr(callback, '__code__'):
2361            if callback.__code__.co_argcount == 2:
2362                index = AutoIncrementIndex()
2363                return lambda x: callback(x, index()) 
2364            if callback.__code__.co_argcount == 3:
2365                index = AutoIncrementIndex()
2366                return lambda x: callback(x, index(), self)
2367        return callback
2368
2369
2370class AutoIncrementIndex:
2371    idx = 0
2372    def __call__(self) -> int:
2373        val = self.idx
2374        self.idx += 1
2375        return val
2376
2377
2378class SequenceTransform(Generic[IterableS, T], Iterable[T]):
2379    _iter: IterableS
2380    _cache: Optional[List[T]]
2381
2382    def __init__(self, iterable: IterableS) -> None:
2383        super().__init__()
2384        self._iter = iterable
2385        self._cache = None
2386    
2387    def __iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
2388        if self._cache:
2389            yield from self._cache
2390        else:
2391            cache: List[T] = []
2392            for x in self.__do_iter__():
2393                cache.append(x)
2394                yield x
2395            self._cache = cache
2396
2397    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[T] :
2398        yield from self._iter
2399
2400    def __len__(self) -> int:
2401        if not isinstance(self._iter, SequenceTransform):
2402            # not Sequence, just a wrapper of List, Tuple.etc.
2403            # we can get lenght of it directly.
2404            if hasattr(self._iter, '__len__'):
2405                return len(self._iter) # type: ignore
2406            elif hasattr(self._iter, '__length_hint__'):
2407                return self._iter.__length_hint__() # type: ignore
2408        # we need iterate all to get length
2409        cache = self._cache
2410        if cache is None:
2411            for _ in self:
2412                pass
2413            cache = self._cache
2414        if cache is not None:
2415            return len(cache)
2416        return 0
2417    
2418    def as_sequence(self) -> Sequence[T]:
2419        return it(self)
2420
2421
2422class FilteringTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], T]):
2423    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> None:
2424        super().__init__(iterable)
2425        self._predicate = predicate
2426    
2427    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
2428        for i in self._iter:
2429            if self._predicate(i):
2430                yield i

2436        self._transform = transform

2439        for i in self._iter:

2443class ParallelMappingTransform(SequenceTransform[Sequence[T], R]):
2444    Executor = Literal['Thread', 'Process']
2445
2446    def __init__(
2447            self, 
2448            iterable: Sequence[T], 
2449            transformer: Callable[[T], R], 
2450            max_workers: Optional[int]=None, 
2451            chunksize: int=1,
2452            executor: ParallelMappingTransform.Executor = 'Thread') -> None:
2453
2454        super().__init__(iterable)
2455        self._transformer = transformer
2456        self._max_workers = max_workers
2457        self._executor = executor
2458        self._chunksize = chunksize
2459    
2460    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[R]:
2461        import os
2462
2463        def create_executor(max_workers: int):
2464            if self._executor == 'Process':
2465                from concurrent.futures import ProcessPoolExecutor
2466                return ProcessPoolExecutor(max_workers=max_workers)
2467            else:
2468                from concurrent.futures import ThreadPoolExecutor
2469                return ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=max_workers, thread_name_prefix='PyIter worker')
2470
2471        chunksize = self._chunksize
2472        max_workers = self._max_workers or min(32, (os.cpu_count() or 1) + 4)
2473        batch_size = max_workers * chunksize
2474        
2475        for batch in self._iter.chunked(batch_size):
2476            with create_executor(max_workers) as executor:
2477                yield from executor.map(self._transformer, batch, chunksize=chunksize)
2478

2510class DropWhileTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], T]):
2511    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> None:
2512        super().__init__(iterable)
2513        self._predicate = predicate
2514    
2515    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
2516        drop_state = True
2517        for e in self._iter:
2518            if drop_state and self._predicate(e):
2519                continue
2520            else:
2521                drop_state = False
2522            yield e

2551class MergingTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], V]):
2552    def __init__(self, 
2553        iterable: Iterable[T], 
2554        other: Iterable[R],
2555        transformer: Callable[[T, R], V] = lambda a,b:(a,b)
2556    ) -> None:
2557        super().__init__(iterable)
2558        self._other = other
2559        self._transformer = transformer
2560    
2561    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[V]:
2562        iter1 = iter(self._iter)
2563        iter2 = iter(self._other)
2564        while True:
2565            try:
2566                yield self._transformer(next(iter1), next(iter2))
2567            except StopIteration:
2568                break

2571class IntersectionTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[Iterable[T]], T]):
2572    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[Iterable[T]]) -> None:
2573        super().__init__(iterable)
2574    
2575    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
2576        iters = it(self._iter)
2577        seen: Set[T] = set()
2578        for v in iters.first():
2579            if v not in seen and iters.all(lambda iter: v in iter):
2580                yield v
2581                seen.add(v)
2582

2584class MergingWithNextTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], V]):
2585    def __init__(self, 
2586    iterable: Iterable[T], 
2587    transformer: Callable[[T, T], V] = lambda a,b:(a,b)) -> None:
2588        super().__init__(iterable)
2589        self._transformer = transformer
2590    
2591    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[V]:
2592        it = iter(self._iter)
2593        try:
2594            c = next(it)
2595            while True:
2596                n = next(it)
2597                yield self._transformer(c, n)
2598                c = n
2599        except StopIteration:
2600            pass

2603class DistinctTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], T]):
2604    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], key_selector: Optional[Callable[[T], Any]]=None) -> None:
2605        super().__init__(iterable)
2606        self._key_selector = key_selector
2607    
2608    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
2609        seen: Set[Any] = set()
2610        for e in self._iter:
2611            k = self._key_selector(e) if self._key_selector else e
2612            if k not in seen:
2613                seen.add(k)
2614                yield e

2617class Grouping(NamedTuple, Generic[K, T]):
2618    key: K
2619    values: Sequence[T]
2620
2621
2622class GroupingTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], Grouping[K, T]]):
2623    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], key_func: Callable[[T], K]) -> None:
2624        super().__init__(iterable)
2625        self._key_func = key_func
2626    
2627    @property
2628    def keys(self) -> Sequence[K]:
2629        return it(self).map(lambda x: x.key)
2630    
2631    @property
2632    def values(self) -> Sequence[Sequence[T]]:
2633        return it(self).map(lambda x: x.values)
2634    
2635    @property
2636    def items(self) -> Sequence[Grouping[K, T]]:
2637        return it(self)
2638    
2639    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[Grouping[K, T]]:
2640        from collections import defaultdict
2641        d: DefaultDict[K, List[T]] = defaultdict(list)
2642        for e in self._iter:
2643            d[self._key_func(e)].append(e)
2644        yield from it(d.items()).map(lambda x: Grouping(x[0], it(x[1])))

2647class CombinationTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], Tuple[T, ...]]):
2648    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], n: int) -> None:
2649        super().__init__(iterable)
2650        self._n = n
2651    
2652    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[Tuple[T, ...]]:
2653        from itertools import combinations
2654        yield from combinations(self._iter, self._n)

2657class WindowedTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], List[T]]):
2658    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], size: int, step: int, partialWindows :bool) -> None:
2659        super().__init__(iterable)
2660        self._size = size
2661        self._step = step
2662        self._partialWindows = partialWindows
2663    
2664    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[List[T]]:
2665        from collections import deque
2666        window: Deque[T] = deque(maxlen=self._size)
2667        for e in self._iter:
2668            window.append(e)
2669            if len(window) == self._size:
2670                yield list(window)
2671            if len(window) == self._size:
2672                for _ in range(self._step):
2673                    window.popleft()
2674        
2675        if self._partialWindows and len(window) > 0:
2676            yield list(window)

2688class ShufflingTransform(SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], T]):
2689    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T], random: Optional[Union[Random, str, int]]=None) -> None:
2690        super().__init__(iterable)
2691        if random is None or isinstance(random, (str, int)):
2692            from random import Random
2693            self._random = Random(random)
2694        else:
2695            self._random = random
2696    
2697    def __do_iter__(self) -> Iterator[T]:
2698        lst = list(self._iter)
2699        self._random.shuffle(lst)
2700        yield from lst

2731class SequenceProducer:
2732    @overload
2733    def __call__(self, elements: List[T]) -> Sequence[T]:
2734        ...
2735    @overload
2736    def __call__(self, elements: Iterable[T]) -> Sequence[T]:
2737        ...
2738    @overload
2739    def __call__(self, *elements: T) -> Sequence[T]:
2740        ...
2741    def __call__(self, *iterable: Union[Iterable[T], List[T], T]) -> Sequence[T]: # type: ignore
2742        if len(iterable) == 1:
2743            iter = iterable[0]
2744            if isinstance(iter, Sequence):
2745                return iter # type: ignore
2746            if isinstance(iter, Iterable) and not isinstance(iter, str):
2747                return Sequence(iter) # type: ignore
2748        return Sequence(iterable) # type: ignore
2749    
2750    def json(self, filepath: str, **kwargs: Dict[str, Any]) -> Sequence[Any]:
2751        """
2752        Reads and parses the input of a json file.
2753        """
2754        import json
2755        with open(filepath, 'r') as f:
2756            data = json.load(f, **kwargs) # type: ignore
2757            return self(data)
2758    
2759    def csv(self, filepath: str):
2760        """
2761        Reads and parses the input of a csv file.
2762        """
2763        import csv
2764        with open(filepath) as f:
2765            r = csv.reader(f)
2766            return it(r)

class Sequence(typing.Generic[~T], typing.Iterable[~T]): 
  29class Sequence(Generic[T], Iterable[T]):
  30    """
  31    Given an [iterator] function constructs a [Sequence] that returns values through the [Iterator]
  32    provided by that function.
  33    
  34    The values are evaluated lazily, and the sequence is potentially infinite.
  35    """
  36    _iter: SequenceTransform[Iterable[T], T]
  37
  38    def __init__(self, iterable: Iterable[T]) -> None:
  39        super().__init__()
  40        if not isinstance(isinstance, SequenceTransform):
  41            iterable = SequenceTransform(iterable)
  42        self._iter = iterable
  43
  44    @overload
  45    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  46        ...
  47    @overload
  48    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  49        ...
  50    @overload
  51    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  52        ...
  53    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  54        """
  55        Returns a Sequence containing only elements matching the given [predicate].
  56
  57        Example 1:
  58        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
  59        >>> it(lst).filter(lambda x: x.startswith('a')).to_list()
  60        ['a1', 'a2']
  61
  62        Example 2:
  63        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
  64        >>> it(lst).filter(lambda x, i: x.startswith('a') or i % 2 == 0 ).to_list()
  65        ['a1', 'b2', 'a2']
  66        """
  67        return FilteringTransform(self, self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)).as_sequence()
  68
  69    @deprecated(reason="use `.filter(lambda x, idx: ... )` instead.")
  70    def filter_indexed(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  71        return self.filter(predicate)
  72
  73    def filter_is_instance(self, typ: Type[R]) -> Sequence[R]:
  74        """
  75        Returns a Sequence containing all elements that are instances of specified type parameter typ.
  76
  77        Example 1:
  78        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 1, 'b2', 3]
  79        >>> it(lst).filter_is_instance(int).to_list()
  80        [1, 3]
  81
  82        """
  83        return self.filter(lambda x: isinstance(x, typ)) # type: ignore
  84    @overload
  85    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  86        ...
  87    @overload
  88    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  89        ...
  90    @overload
  91    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  92        ...
  93    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
  94        """
  95        Returns a Sequence containing all elements not matching the given [predicate].
  96
  97        Example 1:
  98        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
  99        >>> it(lst).filter_not(lambda x: x.startswith('a')).to_list()
 100        ['b1', 'b2']
 101
 102        Example 2:
 103        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'a2', 'b1', 'b2']
 104        >>> it(lst).filter_not(lambda x, i: x.startswith('a') and i % 2 == 0 ).to_list()
 105        ['a2', 'b1', 'b2']
 106        """
 107        predicate = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
 108        return self.filter(lambda x: not predicate(x))
 109
 110    def filter_not_none(self) -> Sequence[T]:
 111        """
 112        Returns a Sequence containing all elements that are not `None`.
 113
 114        Example 1:
 115        >>> lst = [ 'a', None, 'b']
 116        >>> it(lst).filter_not_none().to_list()
 117        ['a', 'b']
 118        """
 119        return self.filter(lambda x: x is not None)

 121    @overload
 122    def map(self, transform: Callable[[T], R]) -> Sequence[R]:
 123        ...
 124    @overload
 125    def map(self, transform: Callable[[T, int], R]) -> Sequence[R]:
 126        ...
 127    @overload
 128    def map(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], R]) -> Sequence[R]:
 129        ...
 130    def map(self, transform: Callable[..., R]) -> Sequence[R]:
 131        """
 132        Returns a Sequence containing the results of applying the given [transform] function
 133        to each element in the original Sequence.
 134
 135        Example 1:
 136        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 137        >>> it(lst).map(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 138        [12, 13]
 139
 140        Example 2:
 141        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 142        >>> it(lst).map(lambda x, i: x['name'] + str(i)).to_list()
 143        ['A0', 'B1']
 144
 145        Example 3:
 146        >>> lst = ['hi', 'abc']
 147        >>> it(lst).map(len).to_list()
 148        [2, 3]
 149        """
 150        return MappingTransform(self, self._callback_overload_warpper(transform)).as_sequence()
 151    
 152    @deprecated(reason="use `.map(lambda x, idx: ... )` instead.")
 153    def map_indexed(self, transform: Callable[[T, int], R]) -> Sequence[R]:
 154        return self.map(transform)
 155    
 156    async def map_async(self, transform: Callable[..., Coroutine[Any, Any, R]]) -> Sequence[R]:
 157        """
 158        Similar to `.map()` but you can input a async transform then await it.
 159        """
 160        from asyncio import gather
 161        return it(await gather(*self.map(transform))) # type: ignore
 162
 163    @overload
 164    def map_not_none(self, transform: Callable[[T], Optional[R]]) -> Sequence[R]:
 165        ...
 166    @overload
 167    def map_not_none(self, transform: Callable[[T, int], Optional[R]]) -> Sequence[R]:
 168        ...
 169    @overload
 170    def map_not_none(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], Optional[R]]) -> Sequence[R]:
 171        ...
 172    def map_not_none(self, transform: Callable[..., Optional[R]]) -> Sequence[R]:
 173        """
 174        Returns a Sequence containing only the non-none results of applying the given [transform] function
 175        to each element in the original collection.
 176
 177        Example 1:
 178        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 179        >>> it(lst).map_not_none(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 180        [12]
 181        """
 182        return self.map(transform).filter_not_none() # type: ignore
 183    
 184    @overload
 185    def parallel_map(self, transform: Callable[[T], R], max_workers: Optional[int]=None, chunksize: int=1, executor: ParallelMappingTransform.Executor='Thread') -> Sequence[R]:
 186        ...
 187    @overload
 188    def parallel_map(self, transform: Callable[[T, int], R], max_workers: Optional[int]=None, chunksize: int=1, executor: ParallelMappingTransform.Executor='Thread') -> Sequence[R]:
 189        ...
 190    @overload
 191    def parallel_map(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], R], max_workers: Optional[int]=None, chunksize: int=1, executor: ParallelMappingTransform.Executor='Thread') -> Sequence[R]:
 192        ...
 193    def parallel_map(self, transform: Callable[..., R], max_workers: Optional[int]=None, chunksize: int=1, executor: ParallelMappingTransform.Executor='Thread') -> Sequence[R]:
 194        """
 195        Returns a Sequence containing the results of applying the given [transform] function
 196        to each element in the original Sequence.
 197
 198        Example 1:
 199        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 200        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 201        [12, 13]
 202
 203        Example 2:
 204        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 205        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x: x['age'], max_workers=2).to_list()
 206        [12, 13]
 207
 208        Example 3:
 209        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 210        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x, i: x['age'] + i, max_workers=2).to_list()
 211        [12, 14]
 212        """
 213        return ParallelMappingTransform(self, self._callback_overload_warpper(transform), max_workers, chunksize, executor).as_sequence()
 214

 224    def find(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 225        """
 226        Returns the first element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if no such element was found.
 227        
 228        Example 1:
 229        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 230        >>> it(lst).find(lambda x: x == 'b')
 231        'b'
 232        """
 233        return self.first_or_none(predicate)

 248        ...

 251        ...

 253    def first(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> T:
 254        ...
 255    @overload
 256    def first(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T:
 257        ...
 258    def first(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 259        """
 260        Returns first element.
 261
 262        Example 1:
 263        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 264        >>> it(lst).first()
 265        'a'
 266
 267        Example 2:
 268        >>> lst = []
 269        >>> it(lst).first()
 270        Traceback (most recent call last):
 271        ...
 272        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 273
 274        Example 3:
 275        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 276        >>> it(lst).first(lambda x: x == 'b')
 277        'b'
 278
 279        Example 4:
 280        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 281        >>> it(lst).first(lambda x: x == 'd')
 282        Traceback (most recent call last):
 283        ...
 284        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 285
 286        Example 5:
 287        >>> lst = [None]
 288        >>> it(lst).first() is None
 289        True
 290        """
 291        for e in self:
 292            if predicate is None or predicate(e):
 293                return e
 294        raise ValueError("Sequence is empty.")

 308        ...
 309    def first_not_none_of(self: Sequence[Optional[R]], transform: Optional[Callable[..., Optional[R]]] = None) -> R:
 310        """
 311        Returns the first non-`None` result of applying the given [transform] function to each element in the original collection.
 312
 313        Example 1:
 314        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 12}]
 315        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of(lambda x: x['age'])
 316        12
 317
 318        Example 2:
 319        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 320        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of(lambda x: x['age'])
 321        Traceback (most recent call last):
 322        ...
 323        ValueError: No element of the Sequence was transformed to a non-none value.
 324        """
 325
 326        v = self.first_not_none_of_or_none() if transform is None else self.first_not_none_of_or_none(transform)
 327        if v is None:
 328            raise ValueError('No element of the Sequence was transformed to a non-none value.')
 329        return v
 330    
 331    @overload
 332    def first_not_none_of_or_none(self) -> T:
 333        ...
 334    @overload
 335    def first_not_none_of_or_none(self, transform: Callable[[T], T]) -> T:
 336        ...
 337    @overload
 338    def first_not_none_of_or_none(self, transform: Callable[[T, int], T]) -> T:
 339        ...
 340    @overload
 341    def first_not_none_of_or_none(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], T]) -> T:
 342        ...
 343    def first_not_none_of_or_none(self, transform: Optional[Callable[..., T]] = None) -> T:
 344        """
 345        Returns the first non-`None` result of applying the given [transform] function to each element in the original collection.
 346
 347        Example 1:
 348        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 12}]
 349        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of_or_none(lambda x: x['age'])
 350        12
 351
 352        Example 2:
 353        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 354        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of_or_none(lambda x: x['age']) is None
 355        True
 356        """
 357        if transform is None:
 358            return self.first_or_none()
 359        return self.map_not_none(transform).first_or_none()

 369        ...

 372        ...
 373    def first_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 374        """
 375        Returns the first element, or `None` if the Sequence is empty.
 376
 377        Example 1:
 378        >>> lst = []
 379        >>> it(lst).first_or_none() is None
 380        True
 381
 382        Example 2:
 383        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 384        >>> it(lst).first_or_none()
 385        'a'
 386
 387        Example 2:
 388        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 389        >>> it(lst).first_or_none(lambda x: x == 'b')
 390        'b'
 391        """
 392        return next(iter(self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate)), None)

 395    @overload

 397        ...

 400        ...

 403        ...
 404    @overload
 405    def first_or_default(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool], default: T) -> T :
 406        ...
 407    def first_or_default(self, predicate: Union[Callable[..., bool], T], default: Optional[T] = None) -> T: # type: ignore
 408        """
 409        Returns the first element, or the given [default] if the Sequence is empty.
 410
 411        Example 1:
 412        >>> lst = []
 413        >>> it(lst).first_or_default('a')
 414        'a'
 415
 416        Example 2:
 417        >>> lst = ['b']
 418        >>> it(lst).first_or_default('a')
 419        'b'
 420        
 421        Example 3:
 422        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 423        >>> it(lst).first_or_default(lambda x: x == 'b', 'd')
 424        'b'
 425
 426        Example 4:
 427        >>> lst = []
 428        >>> it(lst).first_or_default(lambda x: x == 'b', 'd')
 429        'd'
 430        """
 431        if isinstance(predicate, Callable):
 432            return self.first_or_none(predicate) or default # type: ignore
 433        else:
 434            default = predicate
 435        return self.first_or_none() or default

 448        ...
 449    def last(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 450        """
 451        Returns last element.
 452
 453        Example 1:
 454        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 455        >>> it(lst).last()
 456        'c'
 457
 458        Example 2:
 459        >>> lst = []
 460        >>> it(lst).last()
 461        Traceback (most recent call last):
 462        ...
 463        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 464        """
 465        v = self.last_or_none(predicate) if predicate is not None else self.last_or_none()
 466        if v is None:
 467            raise ValueError('Sequence is empty.')
 468        return v

 470    @overload
 471    def last_or_none(self) -> Optional[T]:
 472        ...

 474    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 475        ...

 478        ...

 481        ...
 482    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 483        """
 484        Returns the last element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if no such element was found.
 485
 486        Exmaple 1:
 487        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 488        >>> it(lst).last_or_none()
 489        'c'
 490
 491        Exmaple 2:
 492        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 493        >>> it(lst).last_or_none(lambda x: x != 'c')
 494        'b'
 495
 496        Exmaple 3:
 497        >>> lst = []
 498        >>> it(lst).last_or_none(lambda x: x != 'c') is None
 499        True
 500        """
 501        last: Optional[T] = None
 502        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
 503            last = i
 504        return last

 506    def index_of(self, element: T) -> int:
 507        """
 508        Returns first index of [element], or -1 if the collection does not contain element.
 509         
 510        Example 1:
 511        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 512        >>> it(lst).index_of('b')
 513        1
 514
 515        Example 2:
 516        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 517        >>> it(lst).index_of('d')
 518        -1
 519        """
 520        for i, x in enumerate(self._iter):
 521            if x == element:
 522                return i
 523        return -1
 524    
 525    def last_index_of(self, element: T) -> int:
 526        """
 527         Returns last index of [element], or -1 if the collection does not contain element.
 528         
 529        Example 1:
 530        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'b']
 531        >>> it(lst).last_index_of('b')
 532        3
 533
 534        Example 2:
 535        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 536        >>> it(lst).last_index_of('d')
 537        -1
 538        """
 539        seq = self.reversed()
 540        last_idx = len(seq) - 1;
 541        for i, x in enumerate(seq):
 542            if x == element:
 543                return last_idx - i
 544        return -1
 545

 555    def index_of_first(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> int:
 556        """
 557        Returns first index of element matching the given [predicate], or -1 if no such element was found.
 558         
 559        Example 1:
 560        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 561        >>> it(lst).index_of_first(lambda x: x == 'b')
 562        1
 563
 564        Example 2:
 565        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 566        >>> it(lst).index_of_first(lambda x: x == 'd')
 567        -1
 568        """
 569        predicate = self._callback_overload_warpper(predicate)
 570        for i, x in enumerate(self._iter):
 571            if predicate(x):
 572                return i
 573        return -1

 583        ...
 584    def index_of_last(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> int:
 585        """
 586        Returns last index of element matching the given [predicate], or -1 if no such element was found.
 587         
 588        Example 1:
 589        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'b']
 590        >>> it(lst).index_of_last(lambda x: x == 'b')
 591        3
 592
 593        Example 2:

 596        -1
 597        """
 598        seq = self.reversed()
 599        last_idx = len(seq) - 1;

 603                return last_idx - i

 606    @overload
 607    def single(self) -> T:
 608        ...
 609    @overload
 610    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> T:
 611        ...
 612    @overload
 613    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> T:
 614        ...
 615    @overload
 616    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T:
 617        ...
 618    def single(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 619        """
 620        Returns the single element matching the given [predicate], or throws exception if there is no
 621        or more than one matching element.
 622
 623        Exmaple 1:
 624        >>> lst = ['a']
 625        >>> it(lst).single()
 626        'a'
 627
 628        Exmaple 2:
 629        >>> lst = []
 630        >>> it(lst).single() is None
 631        Traceback (most recent call last):
 632        ...
 633        ValueError: Sequence contains no element matching the predicate.
 634
 635        Exmaple 2:
 636        >>> lst = ['a', 'b']
 637        >>> it(lst).single() is None
 638        Traceback (most recent call last):
 639        ...
 640        ValueError: Sequence contains more than one matching element.
 641        """
 642        single: Optional[T] = None
 643        found = False
 644        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
 645            if found:
 646                raise ValueError('Sequence contains more than one matching element.')
 647            single = i
 648            found = True
 649        if single is None:
 650            raise ValueError('Sequence contains no element matching the predicate.')
 651        return single
 652
 653    @overload
 654    def single_or_none(self) -> Optional[T]:
 655        ...
 656    @overload
 657    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 658        ...
 659    @overload
 660    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 661        ...
 662    @overload
 663    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 664        ...
 665    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 666        """
 667        Returns the single element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if element was not found
 668        or more than one element was found.
 669
 670        Exmaple 1:
 671        >>> lst = ['a']
 672        >>> it(lst).single_or_none()
 673        'a'
 674
 675        Exmaple 2:
 676        >>> lst = []
 677        >>> it(lst).single_or_none() is None
 678        True
 679
 680        Exmaple 2:
 681        >>> lst = ['a', 'b']
 682        >>> it(lst).single_or_none() is None
 683        True
 684        """
 685        single: Optional[T] = None
 686        found = False
 687        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
 688            if found:
 689                return None
 690            single = i
 691            found = True
 692        if not found:
 693            return None
 694        return single

 696    # noinspection PyShadowingNames
 697    def drop(self, n: int) -> Sequence[T]:
 698        """
 699        Returns a Sequence containing all elements except first [n] elements.
 700
 701        Example 1:
 702        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 703        >>> it(lst).drop(0).to_list()
 704        ['a', 'b', 'c']
 705
 706        Example 2:
 707        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 708        >>> it(lst).drop(1).to_list()
 709        ['b', 'c']
 710
 711        Example 2:
 712        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 713        >>> it(lst).drop(4).to_list()
 714        []
 715        """
 716        if n < 0:
 717            raise ValueError(f'Requested element count {n} is less than zero.')
 718        if n == 0:
 719            return self
 720
 721        return DropTransform(self, n).as_sequence()
 722
